              id: 'authentication',
              label: 'Authentication & Zero-Trust',
              short: 'AUTH',
              description: 'Per §3.7.2.2 and Table 3-83: mandatory packet authentication plus replay controls under an explicitly untrusted network model.',
              longDescription: `Authentication policy is verify-then-use: if tag validation fails, packet is dropped before any payload-dependent state transition. UET assumes zero trust for in-fabric devices; switches and in-path telemetry are treated as potentially faulty or adversarial and therefore cannot authorize data correctness. Anti-replay uses a sliding acceptance window [S_low, S_high]: packets below low edge are rejected as stale, packets ahead of high edge are held/rejected per policy, and only unseen in-window sequence numbers are accepted. This blocks replay/injection even when packet structure is syntactically valid. Trimmed packets are explicitly constrained to congestion signaling effects only and are never accepted as payload truth. Combined with JobID scoping, this yields tenant-isolated cryptographic domains where cross-job spoof attempts fail at both namespace and auth layers.`,
